The paper proposes a decomposition approach to solve the max-min fair curriculum-based course timetabling problem, which involves optimizing the allocation of courses to time slots and rooms while ensuring fairness among students. This problem is relevant to several subfields of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI) for optimization and decision-making, data structures (cs.DS) for efficient algorithms, machine learning (cs.LG) for modeling and prediction, robotics (cs.RO) for scheduling and resource allocation, and systems and control (cs.SY) for optimization and coordination. The paper's focus on algorithmic efficiency and performance evaluation also suggests a strong connection to theoretical computer science (cs.TH).
